{"title_page": "Mako (actor)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Mako (disambiguation){{!}}Mako}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Japanese name|Iwamatsu}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mako\n| image              = Makopicture.jpg\n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \u5ca9\u677e \u4fe1\n| native_name_lang   = ja\n| birth_name         = Makoto Iwamatsu\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1933|12|10}}\n| birth_place        = {{nowrap|[[Kobe]], [[Hy\u014dgo Prefecture|Hy\u014dgo]], [[Empire of Japan]]}}\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2006|7|21|1933|12|10}}\n| death_place        = [[Somis, California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Pasadena Playhouse]]\n| other_names        = Mako Iwamatsu\n| children           = 2\n| occupation         = Live-action actor, voice actor\n| years_active       = 1959\u20132006\n| spouse             = [[Shizuko Hoshi]]\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Makoto Iwamatsu'''|\u5ca9\u677e \u4fe1|Iwamatsu Makoto|December 10, 1933 \u2013 July 21, 2006}} was a [[Japanese Americans|Japanese-American]] live-action and voice actor; almost all of his acting roles credited him as '''Mako'''.\n\nHis film roles include Po-Han in ''[[The Sand Pebbles (film)|The Sand Pebbles]]'' (1966) (for which he was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]), Oomiak \"The Fearless One\" in ''[[The Island at the Top of the World]]'' (1974),<ref>\"The Island at the Top of the World\" Wikipage</ref> Akiro the Wizard in ''[[Conan the Barbarian (1982 film)|Conan the Barbarian]]'' (1982) and ''[[Conan the Destroyer]]'' (1984), and Kungo [[Tsarong]] in ''[[Seven Years in Tibet (1997 film)|Seven Years in Tibet]]'' (1997). He was part of the original cast of [[Stephen Sondheim]]'s 1976 [[Broadway musical]] ''[[Pacific Overtures]]'', which earned him a [[Tony Award]] nomination for [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]]. He was also one of the founding members of [[East West Players]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eastwestplayers.org/about-us/|title=About|last=Team|first=EWP Web|website=East West Players|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n\nLater in his career, he became well known for his voice acting roles, including Aku in ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' (2001\u20132004), and [[Iroh]] in ''[[Avatar: The Last Airbender]]'' (2005\u20132006). He has a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 7095 Hollywood Blvd.\n\n==Early life==\nMako was born Makoto Iwamatsu<ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\">{{cite news|title= Mako, 72; Actor Opened Door for Asian Americans |work= [[Los Angeles Times]]|date=|url= http://articles.latimes.com/2006/jul/23/local/me-mako23 |accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref> in [[Kobe]], [[Japan]], the son of noted children's book authors and illustrators [[Mitsu Yashima|Tomoe Sasako]] and [[Taro Yashima|Atsushi Iwamatsu]]. In 1939 his parents, who were political dissidents, moved to the United States, leaving Mako in the care of his grandmother.<ref name=pulvers/><ref name=stone>{{cite news|author=Judy Stone |url=http://www.sfgate.com/performance/article/An-unlikely-heroine-of-World-War-II-2569670.php |title=An unlikely heroine of World War II |newspaper=SFGate |date=2007-03-18 |accessdate=2014-02-04}}</ref> After the war, his parents were able to arrange for him to join them in 1949. He enlisted in the military in the 1950s and became a naturalized American citizen in 1956.<ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\"/> When Mako first joined his parents in the United States, he studied architecture. During his military service, he discovered his theatrical talent and trained at the [[Pasadena Playhouse|Pasadena Community Playhouse]].<ref name=pulvers>{{citation |last=Pulvers |first=Roger |title=Mako: the Japanese-American actor who fought racist stereotypes | newspaper=[[The Japan Times]] |date=September 18, 2011 |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/opinion/2011/09/18/commentary/mako-the-japanese-american-actor-who-fought-racist-stereotypes/}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Film===\nMako's first film role was in the film ''[[Never So Few]]'' (1959). He was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his role as engine-room coolie Po-Han in the film ''[[The Sand Pebbles (film)|The Sand Pebbles]]'' (1966).<ref name=pulvers/> Other roles include the Chinese contract laborer Mun Ki in the epic movie ''[[The Hawaiians (film)|The Hawaiians]]'' (1970) starring [[Charlton Heston]] and [[Tina Chen]]; Oomiak, the Eskimo guide, in Disney's ''[[The Island at the Top of the World]]'' (1974); Yuen Chung in the film ''[[The Killer Elite]]'' (1975) directed by Sam Peckinpah and starring James Caan, Robert Duvall, and the famous martial artist [[Takayuki Kubota]]; the sorcerer Nakano in ''[[Highlander III: The Sorcerer]]''; [[Jackie Chan]]'s uncle/sifu in Chan's first American movie ''[[The Big Brawl]]'' (1980); the wizard Akiro opposite [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] in the two Conan movies ''Conan the Barbarian'' and ''Conan the Destroyer''; the confidant to [[Chuck Norris]]' rogue cop in the thriller ''[[An Eye for an Eye (1981 film)|An Eye for an Eye]]'' (1982); the Japanese spy in the comedy ''[[Under the Rainbow]]''.  In 1990, he had a minor role in the psychological thriller ''[[Pacific Heights]]'' along with [[Matthew Modine]], [[Melanie Griffith]] and [[Michael Keaton]]; Yoshida-san in ''[[Rising Sun (film)|Rising Sun]]''; Mr. Lee in ''[[Sidekicks (1992 film)|Sidekicks]]''; Kanemitsu in ''[[RoboCop 3]]'' (1993); and Kungo Tsarong in ''[[Seven Years in Tibet (1997 film)|Seven Years in Tibet]]'' (1997).\n\nHe also appeared in some Japanese television dramas and films, such as [[Masahiro Shinoda]]'s ''[[Owls' Castle]]'' and [[Takashi Miike]]'s ''[[The Bird People in China]]''.\n\nMako was cast as the historic Admiral [[Isoroku Yamamoto]] in the epic drama ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]'' (2001). He also had a role in ''[[Bulletproof Monk]]'' (2003). In 2005, Mako had a cameo role in ''[[Memoirs of a Geisha (film)|Memoirs of a Geisha]]''. Mako's last leading role was in the film ''[[Cages]]'' (2005), written and directed by [[Graham Streeter]].\n\nMako has a motion picture star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 7095 Hollywood Blvd. He was among the actors, producers and directors interviewed in the 2006 documentary ''[[The Slanted Screen]]'', directed by [[Jeff Adachi]], about the representation of Asian and Asian American men in [[Hollywood]].\n\n===Theater===\nIn 1965, frustrated by the limited roles available to himself and other [[Asian American]] actors, Mako and six others formed the [[East West Players]] theatre company, first performing out of a church basement. The company is one of the earliest [[Asian-American theatre]] organizations, and not only provided a venue for Asian American actors to train and perform, but also nurtured many Asian American playwrights. During the company's 1981 season, to coincide with the [[Commission on Wartime Relocation and Internment of Civilians]]' hearings on [[Japanese American redress and court cases|redress]], Mako exclusively showed plays about the Japanese American incarceration.<ref>{{cite web|last=Niiya |first=Brian |url=http://encyclopedia.densho.org/Mako/ |title=Mako |publisher=Densho Encyclopedia |accessdate=October 29, 2014}}</ref> He remained artistic director of the company until 1989.\n\nMako's [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] career included creating the roles of the Reciter, the ''[[sh\u014dgun]]'', and the [[Chicago]]-based inventor of the [[rickshaw]], in the original 1976 production of [[Stephen Sondheim]]'s [[Broadway musical]] ''[[Pacific Overtures]]'', for which he was nominated for a [[Tony Award for Best Leading Actor in a Musical]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/07/19/specials/sondheim-overtures.html| last=Kerr| first=Walter| title='Pacific Overtures' Is Neither East Nor West| newspaper=[[The New York Times]]| date=January 18, 1976|url-access=subscription }}</ref>  Mako's landlord at the time, [[Jerry Orbach]], was also nominated for his role in ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago]]''; both lost, however, to [[George Rose (actor)|George Rose]] from the revival of ''[[My Fair Lady]]''. Mako recalled being awoken at 4:30 the morning after the Tony ceremony by Orbach, who was shouting from the floor below: \"Hey, Mako! What the fuck happened? I can't believe it; we lost to a fucking revival!\".<ref>{{cite journal| url=https://www.sondheimreview.com/magazine/vol-4-no-4-spring-1998/| title=Three actors recall their roles in the original Broadway production| journal=[[The Sondheim Review]]| date=Spring 1998| volume=4| number=4| access-date=September 13, 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202013357/https://www.sondheimreview.com/magazine/vol-4-no-4-spring-1998/| archive-date=February 2, 2017| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref> Mako reprised the role and directed the musical's production with the East West Players,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stevens |first1=Rob |title=Pacific Overtures reviewed by Rob Stevens |url=http://www.haineshisway.com/2017/12/pacific-overtures-reviewed-by-rob-stevens/ |website=Haineshisway.com |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> and further reprised the role in a production at the San Jose Civic Light Opera in 1991.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chang |first1=Lia |title=Lucille Lortel Nominee Thom Sesma Talks Asian American Representation in the Performing Arts |url=https://backstagepasswithliachang.wordpress.com/2018/04/12/lucille-lortel-nominee-thom-sesma-talks-asian-american-representation-in-the-performing-arts/ |website=Backstage Pass with Lia Chang |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> He also starred in the limited run of the play ''Shimada'' in 1992.\n\n===Television===\nMako appeared on the television series ''[[McHale's Navy]]'' several times, playing Imperial Japanese officers, soldiers and sailors. In 1965, he appeared on \u201cGidget\u201d as a member of a rival surf group. He later appeared on the television series ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'', playing multiple roles such as a Chinese doctor, North Korean soldier, a South Korean Major medical doctor and a South Korean Lieutenant. He appeared in an episode of the series ''[[The Time Tunnel]]'' called \"Kill Two by Two\" as Lt. Nakamura in 1967.  He appeared in an episode of the series ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]'' as Wong Ti Lu in 1972 (\"The Tide\"). In 1974, he appeared on ''[[Ironside (TV series)|Ironside]]'' episode \"Terror on Grant Avenue\". He appeared as a Japanese chef in the ''[[Columbo]]'' episode \"Murder Under Glass\" (1978). He was the blind philosopher Li Sung in two episodes of the television series ''[[The Incredible Hulk (1978 TV series)|The Incredible Hulk]]''. He also appeared on an episode of ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'' called \"The Arrow That Is Not Aimed\" (1983). Mako also appeared in an episode of the television series ''[[F Troop]]''. He appeared as Lo Sing, fighting [[Bruce Lee]]'s [[Kato (The Green Hornet)|Kato]] character in ''[[The Green Hornet (TV series)|The Green Hornet]]'' episode \"The Preying Mantis\". He played the character Lin Duk Coo in an episode of ''[[The A-Team]]''. He guest-starred in an episode of season one of ''[[Frasier]]'' as well as in an episode of ''[[Tour of Duty (TV series)|Tour of Duty]]'' as a Vietnamese scout. He also was a [[guest star]] in the ''[[Monk (TV series)|Monk]]'' episode \"Mr. Monk vs. The Cobra\". He guest-starred in the ''[[Walker, Texas Ranger]]'' episode \"Black Dragons\" (2000), and appeared on the television series ''[[Charmed]]'' in 2003, creating magic for Chris (played by [[Drew Fuller]]). His last \"made-for-TV\" movie appears to be ''[[Rise: Blood Hunter]]'' (2007).\n\nHe was the voice of [[Samurai Jack#Aku|Aku]], the main [[antagonist]] in the animated series ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' for the four original seasons produced, and again in the series finale which used his original audio. He also voiced Achoo (a parody of Aku) and the annoying alarm clock known as Happy Cat in ''[[Duck Dodgers (TV series)|Duck Dodgers]]'', the introductory voice for the ending theme of ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'' and [[Iroh]] in ''Avatar: The Last Airbender''. He had a guest appearance in the [[Nickelodeon]] [[Nickelodeon Movies|movie]] ''[[Rugrats in Paris: The Movie]]'' as the boss of Coco. He guest-starred in ''[[The West Wing]]'' episode \"[[A Good Day (The West Wing)|A Good Day]]\" as an economics professor and former rival of [[Josiah Bartlet|President Bartlet]].\n\n===Video games===\nMako made his video game debut with the role of the goblin Grubjub in ''[[Lionheart: Legacy of the Crusader]]'' (2003). In the same year, he also voiced General Han Yu Kim in ''[[True Crime: Streets of LA]]'', Masataka Shima in ''[[Medal of Honor: Rising Sun]]'', and various voices in ''[[Secret Weapons Over Normandy]]''. In 2004, Mako voiced the narrator in the game ''[[Wrath Unleashed]]'', and Aku in ''[[Samurai Jack: The Shadow of Aku]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nMako was married to actress [[Shizuko Hoshi]], with whom he had two daughters (Mimosa and Sala\u2014both of whom are actresses) and two grandchildren.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/25/arts/25mako.html|title=Mako, 72, Actor Who Extended Asian-American Roles, Dies| date=July 25, 2006| newspaper=The New York Times| accessdate=May 24, 2017|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMako died in [[Somis, California]], on July 21, 2006, at age 72, from [[esophageal cancer]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> One day before his death, Mako had been confirmed to star in the film ''[[TMNT (film)|TMNT]]'' as the voice of [[Master Splinter|Splinter]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.superherohype.com/news.php?id=4522| title=TMNT Bits and Posters!| publisher=SuperHeroHype| date=July 20, 2006| accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref> [[Kevin Munroe]], director of the film, confirmed that Mako had completed his recording.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/display.cgi?id=24228|title=Quint interviews the CGI TEENAGE MUTANT NINJA TURTLES movie director, Kevin Munroe!!!| publisher=Ain't It Cool| accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/45/17245.php| work=MovieWeb| date=January 24, 2007| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206121623/http://www.movieweb.com/news/45/17245.php| archive-date=February 6, 2007| title=On the Set of TMNT!| accessdate=August 11, 2018}}</ref> The producers dedicated the finished film to Mako.\n\nDuring the ''Avatar: The Last Airbender'' episode \"[[The Tales of Ba Sing Se]]\", the segment titled \"The Tale of Iroh\" features a dedication to Mako, the voice actor for Iroh for seasons one and two. In the sequel series ''[[The Legend of Korra]]'', [[Mako (The Legend of Korra)|a lead male character]] was named after him (voiced by [[David Faustino]]).<ref>{{cite web| title=The Legend of Korra| url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1695360/fullcredits/| website=IMDB| publisher=Amazon| accessdate=23 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter Mako's death, some of his roles, particularly Aku from ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' and [[Iroh]] in ''[[Avatar: The Last Airbender]]'' and ''[[The Legend of Korra]]'', were taken over by American voice actor [[Greg Baldwin]].\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1959 || ''[[Never So Few]]'' || Soldier in the hospital|| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1965 || ''[[McHale's Navy Joins the Air Force]]'' || Japanese Submarine Captain|| Uncredited\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1966 || ''[[The Ugly Dachshund]]'' || Kenji ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Sand Pebbles (film)|The Sand Pebbles]]'' || Po-han || Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/Error/NotFound?aspxerrorpath=/search/results|title=Browser Unsupported - Academy Awards Search {{!}} Academy of Motion Picture Arts & Sciences|website=awardsdatabase.oscars.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><br>Nominated \u2013 [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2014 Motion Picture]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/1967/all|title=Winners & Nominees 1967|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1968 || ''[[The Private Navy of Sgt. O'Farrell]]'' || Calvin Coolidge Ishimura ||\n|-\n| 1969 || ''[[The Great Bank Robbery (1969 film)|The Great Bank Robbery]]'' || Secret Agent Fong ||\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1970 || ''[[The Hawaiians (film)|The Hawaiians]]'' || Mun Ki ||\n|-\n| ''[[Fools (film)|Fools]]'' || Psychiatrist ||\n|-\n| 1971 || ''[[Silence (1971 film)|Silence]]'' || Kichijiro ||\n|-\n| 1972 || ''Yokohama Mama'' || Rooster || Voice, Short\n|-\n| 1974 || ''[[The Island at the Top of the World]]'' || Oomiak ||\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1975 || ''Prisoners'' || Sgt. Nguyen ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Killer Elite]]'' || Yuen Chung || \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1980 || ''[[The Big Brawl]]'' || Herbert ||\n|-\n| ''Hito Hata: Raise the Banner'' || Oda ||\n|-\n| rowspan=3|1981 || ''[[Under the Rainbow]]'' || Nakomuri ||\n|-\n| ''[[An Eye for an Eye (1981 film)|An Eye for an Eye]]'' || James Chan ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Bushido Blade]]'' || Enjiro ||\n|-\n| 1982 || ''[[Conan the Barbarian (1982 film)|Conan the Barbarian]]'' || Akiro the Wizard ||\n|-\n| 1983 || ''[[Testament (1983 film)|Testament]]'' || Mike ||\n|-\n| 1984 || ''[[Conan the Destroyer (film)|Conan the Destroyer]]'' || Akiro the Wizard ||\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1986 || ''[[Behind Enemy Lines (1986 film)|Behind Enemy Lines]]'' || Capt. Vinh ||\n|-\n| ''[[Armed Response (1986 film)|Armed Response]]'' || Akira Tanaka ||\n|-\n| rowspan=3|1988 || ''Silent Assassins'' || Oyama ||\n|-\n| ''[[Tucker: The Man and His Dream]]'' || Jimmy ||\n|-\n| ''The Wash'' || Nobu Matsumoto ||\n|-\n| 1989 || ''An Unremarkable Life'' || Max Chin ||\n|-\n| rowspan=3|1990 || ''Pu guang ren wu'' || Trang ||\n|-\n| ''[[Taking Care of Business (film)|Taking Care of Business]]'' || Mr. Saka