sier]]'' || Sam Tanaka || Episode: \"Author, Author\"\n|-\n| 1994, 1996 || ''[[Kung Fu: The Legend Continues]]'' || Li Sung || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Platypus Man]]'' || Mr. Loo || Episode: \"Dying to Live\"\n|-\n| 1996\u20132003 || ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'' || Narrator (voice) || 13 episodes\n|-\n| 1997, 2000 || ''[[Walker, Texas Ranger]]'' || Dr. Henry Lee / Edward Song || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1997 || ''[[Riot (1997 film)|Riot]]'' || Mr. Lee || Television film; segment: \"Gold Mountain\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1999 || ''[[Martial Law (TV series)|Martial Law]]'' || Master Reng || 2 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[7th Heaven (TV series)|7th Heaven]]'' || Henry Muranaka || Episode: \"Dirty Laundry\"\n|-\n| 2000 || ''[[The Secret Adventures of Jules Verne]]'' || Kajimori || Episode: \"The Inquisitor\"\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Diagnosis Murder]]'' || Lee Moy || Episode: \"The Red's Shoes\"\n|-\n| 2001\u20132004 || ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' || Aku (voice) || 24 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|2003 || ''[[Lost at Home]]'' || Mr. Li || Episode: \"Good Will Hunting\"\n|-\n| ''[[Black Sash (TV series)|Black Sash]]'' || Master Li || 6 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[What's New, Scooby-Doo?]]'' || The Ancient One (voice) || Episode: \"Big Appetite in Little Tokyo\"\n|-\n| ''[[Charmed]]'' || Sorcerer || Episode: \"Love's a Witch\"\n|-\n| 2003\u20132005 || ''[[Duck Dodgers (TV series)|Duck Dodgers]]'' || Happy Cat / Achoo (voices) || 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy]]'' || Narrator (voice) || Episode: \"Test of Time/A Kick in the Asgard\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|2005 || ''[[Monk (TV series)|Monk]]'' || Master Zi || Episode: \"Mr. Monk vs. the Cobra\"\n|-\n| ''[[The West Wing]]'' || Dr. Yosh Takahashi || Episode: \"A Good Day\"\n|-\n| ''[[Super Robot Monkey Team Hyperforce Go!]]'' || Master Offay (voice) || Episode: \"Monster Battle Club Now!\"\n|-\n| ''Sokoku'' || Leo || Television film\n|-\n| 2005\u20132006 || ''[[Avatar: The Last Airbender]]'' || Uncle Iroh / Additional voices || 30 episodes\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Voice role\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2003 || ''[[Lionheart: Legacy of the Crusader]]'' || Grumdjum\n|-\n| ''[[True Crime: Streets of LA]]'' || General Kim \n|-\n| ''[[Medal of Honor: Rising Sun]]'' || Masataka Shima \n|-\n| ''[[Secret Weapons Over Normandy]]'' || Imperial Japanese Voices #1\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2004 || ''[[Samurai Jack: The Shadow of Aku]]'' || Aku \n|-\n| ''[[Wrath Unleashed]]'' || Narrator \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Japan}}\n* {{IMDb name|0538683}}\n* {{IBDB name|name=Mako}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes person|mako|Mako}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060626140125/http://www.sondheimreview.com/v4n4.htm#article A 1998 interview] about [[Pacific Overtures]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mako}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male actors of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American dramatists and playwrights of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American theatre directors of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Japanese male film actors]]\n[[Category:Japanese male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Japanese male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Japanese emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Actors from Kobe]]\n[[Category:Male voice actors from Kobe]]\n[[Category:Deaths from esophageal cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n", "name_user": "General Iroh, the Dragon of the West", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mako_(actor)"}
{"title_page": "Shin Sung-mo", "text_new": "{{Korean name|Shin}}\n{{Infobox Prime Minister\n|name          = Shin Sung-mo\n|image         = Shin sung.jpg\n|caption       = Mate at the time of sinseongmo\n|order         = [[Prime Minister of South Korea]]<br>{{small|Acting}}<ref name=bbc000421>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/721616.stm\n|title=New evidence of Korean war killings\n|newspaper = [[BBC]]\n|date = 2000-04-21\n|accessdate = 2010-07-23\n}}</ref>\n|term_start    = April 21, 1950\n|term_end      = November 23, 1950\n|deputy        =\n|predecessor   = [[Lee Beom-seok (Prime Minister)|Lee Beom-seok]]\n|successor     = [[Chang Myon]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1891|10|20|mf=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Uiryeong]], [[Gyeongsang-do]], [[Joseon Dynasty|Joseon]] (now [[Uiryeong]], [[Gyeongsangnam-do]], [[South Korea]])\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1960|05|29|1891|10|20|mf=y}}\n|death_place   = [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]\n| death_cause  = [[Cerebral hemorrhage]]\n|resting_place = [[Daejeon National Cemetery]]\n|citizenship         =  [[South Korean]]\n| nationality         =  [[Korean people|Korean]]\n|religion      =\n|module        = {{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul={{linktext|\uc2e0|\uc131|\ubaa8}}\n|hanja={{linktext|\u7533|\u6027|\u6a21|}}\n|rr=Sin Seong-mo\n|mr=Sin S\u014fngmo\n|hangulho={{linktext|\uc18c|\ucc3d}}\n|hanjaho={{linktext|\u5c0f|\u6ec4}}\n|rrho=Sochang\n|mrho=Soch'ang\n| child  = yes}}\n}}\n'''Shin Sung-mo''' ({{lang-ko|\uc2e0\uc131\ubaa8}}, October 20, 1891 \u2013 May 29, 1960)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kr.dictionary.search.yahoo.com/search/dictionaryp?subtype=enc&pk=15465500&field=id&p=%EC%8B%A0%EC%84%B1%EB%AA%A8 |script-title=ko:\uc2e0\uc131\ubaa8|trans-title=Shin Sung-mo |accessdate=2009-04-11 |url-status=dead|script-work=ko:\uc57c\ud6c4! \ubc31\uacfc\uc0ac\uc804|trans-work=Yahoo! Encyclopedia|language=ko |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120710065113/http://kr.dictionary.search.yahoo.com/search/dictionaryp?subtype=enc&pk=15465500&field=id&p=%EC%8B%A0%EC%84%B1%EB%AA%A8 |archivedate=2012-07-10 }}</ref> was an acting prime minister in 1950 following the first [[prime minister of South Korea]], [[Lee Beom-seok (Prime Minister)|Lee Beom-seok]]. He served as a Defence Minister during the [[Korean War]].<ref name=bbc000421/>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nIn 1891, he was born in [[Uiryeong]], [[Gyeongsang-do]], [[Joseon Dynasty|Joseon]] (now [[Uiryeong]], [[Gyeongsangnam-do]], [[South Korea]]), as the son of Jae rok Lee. In 1907, he entered the night class at the Department of Law at Bosung College, and graduated from Boseong Law College in 1910 (4 years in Yonghee). In August 1910, he fled to [[Vladivostok]] and joined into the [[Korean independence movemen|anti-Japanese independence movement]] under the guidance of Shin Chae-ho and his hometown leader, Ahn Hee-je.\n\nFrom 1930, he became the captain of a regular ferry to and from London and India. When the Korean Liberation Army was established in September 1940, the Provisional Government of the Republic of Korea made a special appointment to him as a military commissioner. During [[World War II]], it was known in Korea that he was surviving around May 1948 after giving up his return and taking office as an adviser to an Indian merchant ship company.\n\n====Political activity====\nHe returned to Korea in 1948. On December 19, 1949, he was invited to the Supreme Council of the Korean Youth.<ref>[http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=B&i=124315&v=42 \ub300\ud55c\uccad\ub144\ub2e8' - \ub124\uc774\ud2b8 \ubc31\uacfc\uc0ac\uc804]</ref> After that, he served as the head of the Korea Youth Team and advisory committee of the Ministry of Transportation, in 1949 he served as the second Minister of Home Affairs ({{lang-ko|\ub300\ud55c\ubbfc\uad6d \ub0b4\ubb34\ubd80}}). On March 21, 1949 he became the second [[Ministry of National Defense (South Korea)|Minister of Defense]] ({{lang-ko|\ub300\ud55c\ubbfc\uad6d \uad6d\ubc29\ubd80}}) a position he held until 5th of May, 1951. Syngman Rhee preferred a person who speaks English well and Shin was said to be fluent in English while studying in London.\n\nUpon returning, he is given the title Admiral. At the time, he served as the captain of a British merchant ship, advisor and director of an Indian merchant ship, but received military training in China and was adjutant to the Chinese Navy Admiral Sal Jinbing, the Korean Provisional Government's Korean Liberation Army Being a member of the military was recognized for his career, he was given the rank of lieutenant general of the Navy, and he was called Admiral Holy Mother.\n\nOn July 17, 1949, while as [[Ministry of National Defense (South Korea)|Minister of National Defense]], he said, \"The military is waiting for orders from the President, and with orders, it can completely take over Pyongyang or [[Wonsan]] within a day.\" When the remarks became a problem, he explained that his remarks were misunderstood, but in early September of that year, he insisted, \"I just wait for the time to come and I'm ready to push.\"\n\nAs [[Lee Beom-seok (prime minister)|Lee Beom-seok]] resigned from his post as Prime Minister, Shin Sung was inaugurated as acting Prime Minister on April 21, 1950, and worked until November 22. \n===Korean War===\n[[image:\uc7a5\uacbd\uadfc \uc2e0\uc131\ubaa8 \uc815\uc77c\uad8c.png|thumb|right|200px|Defense Minister Shin Sung-mo with Deputy Minister of Defense {{Interlanguage link multi|Jang Kyung-geun|ko|3=\uc7a5\uacbd\uadfc}}, and Director [[Chung Il-kwon]] (from left), standing side by side at the Naval Headquarters after the 3rd Army Operation Agreement. Chung Il-kwon was shortly after being issued by the Commander-in-chief of the Army, Naval and Air Force.]]\nThe Korean War broke out and in the beginning of the war, at the [[State Council of South Korea|State Council]] meeting held at 4:00AM on June 27, 1950, Shin Sung-mo who was Minister of Defense said that he had no knowledge of the situation.<ref>\uc804\uc7c1\uae30\ub150\uc0ac\uc5c5\ud68c, \u300a\ud55c\uad6d\uc804\uc7c1\uc0ac 3\uad8c\u300b(\ud589\ub9bc\ucd9c\ud310, 1992) 39\ucabd.</ref>\n\nHe was a member of the Provisional Government Military Committee, but unlike [[Lee Beom-seok (prime minister)|Lee Beom-seok]], [[Ji Cheong-cheon]], [[Kim Hong-il (general)|Kim Hong-il]] and others, he had no experience in direct combat with the army as he was engaged in maritime vessel-related work, communication-related, and interpretation-related work before the repatriation. As a member of the State Council of the Republic of Korea, he showed a completely different attitude from his position to take care of the safety of the people.<ref>[http://allinkorea.net/sub_read.html?uid=38095&section=section11 \n6\u00b725 \ub0a8\uce68\uc804\uc7c1 10\ub300 \ubbf8\uc2a4\ud130\ub9ac\uc758 \uc2e4\uccb4]</ref> At the time of the Korean War, he served as Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\nRegarding the massacre of the [[Geochang massacre]] in 1951, he was criticized by the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]] that it was rationalizing the case with Kim Jong-won ({{lang-ko|\uae40\uc885\uc6d0}}), who was then martial arts commander. It was found that some of the gold was used as political funds for [[Syngman Rhee]]. At this time, Shin Sung-mo resigned as Minister of National Defense while trying to avoid it. In 1951, he worked as the fifth chief executive officer of Japan.\n\nAt this time, [[Chough Pyung-ok]] who was the Minister of Home Affairs ({{lang-ko|\ub300\ud55c\ubbfc\uad6d \ub0b4\ubb34\ubd80}}) and the Prime Minister's office disagreed over his appointment as the Japanese public official, and the Democratic National Party's top member, [[Yun Posun]], also objected by mentioning his morality over the National Defense Force and Geochang massacre, but President Syngman Rhee kneels on their backlash and mocked Shin Sung-mo Japan Corporation jobs were passed.\n\n===After the ceasefire===\nOn November 28, 1956, he served as the Dean of the Maritime University and was sick and died of cerebral hemorrhage at Uiryeong on May 29, 1960. After being buried in Seonyeong, Yongdeok-myeon, Uiryeong-gun, [[South Gyeongsang Province]], it was later transferred to the [[Daejeon National Cemetery]]. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n|before=[[Lee Beom-seok (Prime Minister)|Lee Beom-seok]]\n|after=[[Chang Myon]]\n|title=Acting [[Prime Minister of South Korea]]\n|years=1950\n}}\n{{succession box\n|before=[[Lee Beom-seok (prime minister)|Lee Beom-seok]]\n|after=[[Lee Ki-poong]]\n|title=[[Ministry of National Defense (South Korea)|Minister of National Defence]]\n|years=1949-1951\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of South Korea}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shin, Sung-Mo}}\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:National Defense ministers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:South Korean people of the Korean War]]\n\n\n{{SouthKorea-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Korean name|Shin}}\n{{Infobox Prime Minister\n|name          = Shin Sung-mo\n|image         = Shin sung.jpg\n|caption       = Mate at the time of sinseongmo\n|order         = [[Prime Minister of South Korea]]<br>{{small|Acting}}<ref name=bbc000421>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/721616.stm\n|title=New evidence of Korean war killings\n|newspaper = [[BBC]]\n|date = 2000-04-21\n|accessdate = 2010-07-23\n}}</ref>\n|term_start    = April 21, 1950\n|term_end      = November 23, 1950\n|deputy        =\n|predecessor   = [[Lee Beom-seok (Prime Minister)|Lee Beom-seok]]\n|successor     = [[Chang Myon]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1891|10|20|mf=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Uiryeong]], [[Gyeongsang-do]], [[Joseon Dynasty|Joseon]] (now [[Uiryeong]], [[Gyeongsangnam-do]], [[South Korea]])\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1960|05|29|1891|10|20|mf=y}}\n|death_place   = [[Seoul]], [[South Korea]]\n| death_cause  = [[Cerebral hemorrhage]]\n|resting_place = [[Daejeon National Cemetery]]\n|citizenship         =  [[South Korean]]\n| nationality         =  [[Korean people|Korean]]\n|religion      =\n|module        = {{Infobox Korean name\n|hangul={{linktext|\uc2e0|\uc131|\ubaa8}}\n|hanja={{linktext|\u7533|\u6027|\u6a21|}}\n|rr=Sin Seong-mo\n|mr=Sin S\u014fngmo\n|hangulho={{linktext|\uc18c|\ucc3d}}\n|hanjaho={{linktext|\u5c0f|\u6ec4}}\n|rrho=Sochang\n|mrho=Soch'ang\n| child  = yes}}\n}}\n'''Shin Sung-mo''' ({{lang-ko|\uc2e0\uc131\ubaa8}}, October 20, 1891 \u2013 May 29, 1960)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kr.dictionary.search.yahoo.com/search/dictionaryp?subtype=enc&pk=15465500&field=id&p=%EC%8B%A0%EC%84%B1%EB%AA%A8 |script-title=ko:\uc2e0\uc131\ubaa8|trans-title=Shin Sung-mo |accessdate=2009-04-11 |url-status=dead|script-work=ko:\uc57c\ud6c4! \ubc31\uacfc\uc0ac\uc804|trans-work=Yahoo! Encyclopedia|language=ko |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120710065113/http://kr.dictionary.search.yahoo.com/search/dictionaryp?subtype=enc&pk=15465500&field=id&p=%EC%8B%A0%EC%84%B1%EB%AA%A8 |archivedate=2012-07-10 }}</ref> was an acting prime minister in 1950 following the first [[prime minister of South Korea]], [[Lee Beom-seok (Prime Minister)|Lee Beom-seok]]. He served as a Defence Minister during the [[Korean War]].<ref name=bbc000421/>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nIn 1891, he was born in [[Uiryeong]], [[Gyeongsang-do]], [[Joseon Dynasty|Joseon]] (now [[Uiryeong]], [[Gyeongsangnam-do]], [[South Korea]]), as the son of Jae rok Lee. In 1907, he entered the night class at the Department of Law at Bosung College, and graduated from Boseong Law College in 1910 (4 years in Yonghee). In August 1910, he fled to [[Vladivostok]] and joined into the [[Korean independence movemen|anti-Japanese independence movement]] under the guidance of Shin Chae-ho and his hometown leader, Ahn Hee-je.\n\nFrom 1930, he became the captain of a regular ferry to and from London and India. When the Korean Liberation Army was established in September 1940, the Provisional Government of the Republic of Korea made a special appointment to him as a military commissioner. During [[World War II]], it was known in Korea that he was surviving around May 1948 after giving up his return and taking office as an adviser to an Indian merchant ship company.\n\n====Political activity====\nHe returned to Korea in 1948. On December 19, 1949, he was invited to the Supreme Council of the Korean Youth.<ref>[http://100.nate.com/dicsearch/pentry.html?s=B&i=124315&v=42 \ub300\ud55c\uccad\ub144\ub2e8' - \ub124\uc774\ud2b8 \ubc31\uacfc\uc0ac\uc804]</ref> After that, he served as the head of the Korea Youth Team and advisory committee of the Ministry of Transportation, in 1949 he served as the second Minister of Home Affairs ({{lang-ko|\ub300\ud55c\ubbfc\uad6d \ub0b4\ubb34\ubd80}}). On March 21, 1949 he became the second [[Ministry of National Defense (South Korea)|Minister of Defense]] ({{lang-ko|\ub300\ud55c\ubbfc\uad6d \uad6d\ubc29\ubd80}}) a position he held until 5th of May, 1951. Syngman Rhee preferred a person who speaks English well and Shin was said to be fluent in English while studying in London.\n\nUpon returning, he is given the title Admiral. At the time, he served as the captain of a British merchant ship, advisor and director of an Indian merchant ship, but received military training in China and was adjutant to the Chinese Navy Admiral Sal Jinbing, the Korean Provisional Government's Korean Liberation Army Being a member of the military was recognized for his career, he was given the rank of lieutenant general of the Navy, and he was called Admiral Holy Mother.\n\nOn July 17, 1949, while as [[Ministry of National Defense (South Korea)|Minister of National Defense]], he said, \"The military is waiting for orders from the President, and with orders, it can completely take over Pyongyang or [[Wonsan]] within a day.\" When the remarks became a problem, he explained that his remarks were misunderstood, but in early September of that year, he insisted, \"I just wait for the time to come and I'm ready to push.\"\n\nAs [[Lee Beom-seok (prime minister)|Lee Beom-seok]] resigned from his post as Prime Minister, Shin Sung was inaugurated as acting Prime Minister on April 21, 1950, and worked until November 22. \n===Korean War===\n[[image:\uc7a5\uacbd\uadfc \uc2e0\uc131\ubaa8 \uc815\uc77c\uad8c.png|thumb|right|200px|Defense Minister Shin Sung-mo with Deputy Minister of Defense {{Interlanguage link multi|Jang Kyung-geun|ko|3=\uc7a5\uacbd\uadfc}}, and Director [[Chung Il-kwon]] (from left), standing side by side at the Naval Headquarters after the 3rd Army Operation Agreement. Chung Il-kwon was shortly after being issued by the Commander-in-chief of the Army, Naval and Air Force.]]\nThe Korean War broke out and in the beginning of the war, at the [[State Council of South Korea|State Council]] meeting held at 4:00AM on June 27, 1950, Shin Sung-mo who was Minister of Defense said that he had no knowledge of the situation.<ref>\uc804\uc7c1\uae30\ub150\uc0ac\uc5c5\ud68c, \u300a\ud55c\uad6d\uc804\uc7c1\uc0ac 3\uad8c\u300b(\ud589\ub9bc\ucd9c\ud310, 1992) 39\ucabd.</ref>\n\nHe was a member of the Provisional Government Military Committee, but unlike [[Lee Beom-seok (prime minister)|Lee Beom-seok]], [[Ji Cheong-cheon]], [[Kim Hong-il (general)|Kim Hong-il]] and others, he had no experience in direct combat with the army as he was engaged in maritime vessel-related work, communication-related, and interpretation-related work before the repatriation. As a member of the State Council of the Republic of Korea, he showed a completely different attitude from his position to take care of the safety of the people.<ref>[http://allinkorea.net/sub_read.html?uid=38095&section=section11 \n6\u00b725 \ub0a8\uce68\uc804\uc7c1 10\ub300 \ubbf8\uc2a4\ud130\ub9ac\uc758 \uc2e4\uccb4]</ref> At the time of the Korean War, he served as Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\n\nRegarding the massacre of the [[Geochang massacre]] in 1951, he was criticized by the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]] that it was rationalizing the case with Kim Jong-won ({{lang-ko|\uae40\uc885\uc6d0}}), who was then martial arts commander. It was found that some of the gold was used as political funds for [[Syngman Rhee]]. At this time, Shin Sung-mo resigned as Minister of National Defense while trying to avoid it. In 1951, he worked as the fifth chief executive officer of Japan.\n\nAt this time, [[Chough Pyung-ok]] who was the Minister of Home Affairs ({{lang-ko|\ub300\ud55c\ubbfc\uad6d \ub0b4\ubb34\ubd80}}) and the Prime Minister's office disagreed over his appointment as the Japanese public official, and the Democratic National Party's top member, [[Yun Posun]], also objected by mentioning his morality over the National Defense Force and Geochang massacre, but President Syngman Rhee kneels on their backlash and mocked Shin Sung-mo Japan Corporation jobs were passed.\n\n===After the ceasefire===\nOn November 28, 1956, he served as the Dean of the Maritime University and was sick and died of cerebral hemorrhage at Uiryeong on May 29, 1960. After being buried in Seonyeong, Yongdeok-myeon, Uiryeong-gun, [[South Gyeongsang Province]], it was later transferred to the [[Daejeon National Cemetery]]. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n|before=[[Lee Beom-seok (Prime Minister)|Lee Beom-seok]]\n|after=[[Chang Myon]]\n|title=Acting [[Prime Minister of South Korea]]\n|years=1950\n}}\n{{succession box\n|before=[[Lee Beom-seok]]\n|after=[[Lee Ki-poong]]\n|title=[[Ministry of National Defense (South Korea)|Minister of National Defence]]\n|years=1949-1951\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of South Korea}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shin, Sung-Mo}}\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:National Defense ministers of South Korea]]\n[[Category:South Korean peo