{"title_page": "Disney Sing It", "text_new": "{{original research|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Sing It\n| image        = Disney Sing It.jpg\n| image_size   = 252px\n| caption      =\n| developer    = [[Zo\u00eb Mode]]\n| publisher    = [[Disney Interactive Studios]]\n| designer     = [[Disney Interactive Studios]]\n| engine       =\n|released = {{vgrelease|NA|October 28, 2008}}\n| genre        = [[Music video game|Karaoke]]\n| modes        = [[Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n| platforms    = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Wii]], [[Xbox 360]]\n}}\n'''''Disney Sing It''''' is a [[Music video game|karaoke]] [[video game]]. It was released on October 28, 2008 for the [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Wii]] and [[Xbox 360]].\n\nIt's the second game in the ''Disney Sing It'' series after ''[[High School Musical: Sing It!]]''. The game features 35 songs from [[Disney]]-affiliated artists and [[Disney Channel]] productions like ''[[Hannah Montana]]'', ''[[Camp Rock]]'', [[Aly & AJ]], [[Miley Cyrus]] and the [[Jonas Brothers]]. It also features a selection of songs from the ''[[High School Musical (franchise)|High School Musical]]'' franchise and a \"Singing lessons\" mode with [[Olesya Rulin]] as a vocal coach.\n\nThe game has received mixed reviews, with both [[1UP.com]] and [[IGN]] praising its accessibility towards kids but finding serious fault with the gameplay, with [[Official Xbox Magazine]] ultimately calling it a \"gateway game\" at best.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3171413|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120724133340/http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3171413|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-07-24|title=1UP.com review|accessdate=2008-11-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ps3.ign.com/articles/933/933533p1.html|title=IGN review|accessdate=2008-11-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/games/platforms/xbox360/disneysingit/|title=Metacritic|accessdate=2008-11-28}}</ref>\n\nIt was followed by a third game, ''[[Disney Sing It! \u2013 High School Musical 3: Senior Year]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*''[[High School Musical: Sing It!]]''\n*''[[Disney Sing It! \u2013 High School Musical 3: Senior Year]]''\n*''[[Disney Sing It: Pop Hits]]''\n*''[[Disney Sing It: Party Hits]]''\n*''[[Disney Sing It: Family Hits]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://disney.go.com/disneyinteractivestudios/product.html?platform=ps3&game=Sing_It Official mini-site]\n* [http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/891/891774p1.html/ IGN]\n* [http://www.gearlive.com/news/article/q208-disney-interactive-studios-disney-sing-it-karaoke-game/ Gear Live]\n\n{{High School Musical}}\n{{Disney Sing It}}\n\n[[Category:2008 video games]]\n[[Category:Disney video games]]\n[[Category:High School Musical video games|Sing It!]]\n[[Category:Karaoke video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:Wii games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{original research|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Sing It\n| image        = Disney Sing It.jpg\n| image_size   = 252px\n| caption      =\n| developer    = [[Zo\u00eb Mode]]\n| publisher    = [[Disney Interactive Studios]]\n| designer     = [[Disney Interactive Studios]]\n| engine       =\n|released = {{vgrelease|NA|October 28, 2008}}\n| genre        = [[Music video game|Karaoke]]\n| modes        = [[Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n| platforms    = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Wii]], [[Xbox 360]]\n}}\n'''''Disney Sing It''''' is a [[Music video game|karaoke]] [[video game]]. It was released on October 28, 2008 for the [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Wii]] and [[Xbox 360]].\n\nIt's the second game in the ''Disney Sing It'' series, after ''[[High School Musical: Sing It!]]''. The game features 35 songs from [[Disney]]-affiliated artists and [[Disney Channel]] productions like ''[[Hannah Montana]]'', ''[[Camp Rock]]'', [[Aly & AJ]], [[Miley Cyrus]] and the [[Jonas Brothers]]. It also features a selection of songs from the ''[[High School Musical (franchise)|High School Musical]]'' franchise and a \"Singing lessons\" mode with [[Olesya Rulin]] as a vocal coach.\n\nThe game has received mixed reviews, with both [[1UP.com]] and [[IGN]] praising its accessibility towards kids but finding serious fault with the gameplay, with [[Official Xbox Magazine]] ultimately calling it a \"gateway game\" at best.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3171413|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120724133340/http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3171413|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-07-24|title=1UP.com review|accessdate=2008-11-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ps3.ign.com/articles/933/933533p1.html|title=IGN review|accessdate=2008-11-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/games/platforms/xbox360/disneysingit/|title=Metacritic|accessdate=2008-11-28}}</ref>\n\nIt was followed by a third game, ''[[Disney Sing It! \u2013 High School Musical 3: Senior Year]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*''[[High School Musical: Sing It!]]''\n*''[[Disney Sing It! \u2013 High School Musical 3: Senior Year]]''\n*''[[Disney Sing It: Pop Hits]]''\n*''[[Disney Sing It: Party Hits]]''\n*''[[Disney Sing It: Family Hits]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://disney.go.com/disneyinteractivestudios/product.html?platform=ps3&game=Sing_It Official mini-site]\n* [http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/891/891774p1.html/ IGN]\n* [http://www.gearlive.com/news/article/q208-disney-interactive-studios-disney-sing-it-karaoke-game/ Gear Live]\n\n{{High School Musical}}\n{{Disney Sing It}}\n\n[[Category:2008 video games]]\n[[Category:Disney video games]]\n[[Category:High School Musical video games|Sing It!]]\n[[Category:Karaoke video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:Wii games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "ThomasRibeiro25", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disney_Sing_It"}
{"title_page": "Jam On", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox Radio Station\n| name      = Jam On\n| image     = Sirius jam on.svg\n| area      = [[United States]]<br>[[Canada]]\n| slogan    =\n| airdate   =\n| frequency = [[Sirius XM Radio]] 309<br>[[Dish Network]] 6029\n| format    = [[Jam band|Jam Bands]]\n| owner     = [[Sirius XM Radio]]\n| class     = [[Satellite radio]] station\n| website   = [http://www.siriusxm.com/jamon SiriusXM: Jam On]\n}}\n'''''Jam On''''' is a [[jam band]] radio station on [[Sirius XM Radio]] channel 29 and [[Dish Network]] channel 6081. It has featured basketball player [[Bill Walton]] hosting a [[Grateful Dead]] show, [[hippie]] [[cultural icon|icon]] [[Wavy Gravy]], and pedal steel player [[Buddy Cage]] as a DJ.  It was formed in 2003 by Sirius VP Joel Salkowitz and programmer Lenny Bloch.  The original DJs were Jonathan Schwartz, Stef Scamardo, and Adam Foley.\n\nBy fall 2010, Sirius XM moved ''Jam On'' to channel 81 on the Sirius side to make room for [[Pearl Jam Radio]] on channel 17.  However, Sirius tuners still list channel 81 under the old Cinemagic name, although from 2009\u20132010, that was ''[[The Strobe]]'' on Sirius 81.\n\nThe logo is designed to resemble that of jam band Phish.\n\nThe internet version can be biased toward \"traditional\" songs similar to the roots rock  style of the Grateful Dead, or to \"modern\" songs which are more electronically-based and experimental.\n\nIn June 2019, SiriusXM announced it would be moving JamOn to streaming only to make way for Phish Radio and that listeners could continue to listen to their favorite jam bands for an addition charge for their streaming service online or in the app only.\n\n==Core artists==\n* [[Phish]]\n* [[Gov't Mule]]\n* [[My Morning Jacket]]\n* [[Umphrey's McGee]]\n* [[moe.]]\n* [[Widespread Panic]]\n* [[The Allman Brothers Band]]\n* [[The Grateful Dead]]\n* [[The Disco Biscuits]]\n* [[The String Cheese Incident]]\n* [[Chris Robinson Brotherhood]]\n* [[Dave Matthews Band]]\n\n== Dave Matthews Band Radio ==\nBetween 2009-06-01 and 2009-06-08, the channel featured the music of rock band [[Dave Matthews Band]] 24/7 as well as exclusive interviews.  This  temporarily pre-empted normal programming on the channel.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Dave Matthews Band Radio To Air on SIRIUS XM Radio |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] via xmradio.com |accessdate=4 June 2009 |date=26 May 2009 |url=http://xmradio.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=press_releases&item=1729 |quote=\"Dave Matthews Band Radio\" to broadcast non-stop Dave Matthews Band music, plus exclusive stories from all four band members |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831042619/http://xmradio.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=press_releases |archive-date=31 August 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Sirius Satellite Radio stations]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sirius.com/jamon Sirius Jam On]\n{{SiriusXM Channels (music)}}\n\n[[Category:Sirius Satellite Radio channels]]\n[[Category:XM Satellite Radio channels]]\n[[Category:Digital-only radio stations]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 2003]]\n\n\n{{US-radio-station-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox Radio Station\n| name      = Jam On\n| image     = Sirius jam on.svg\n| area      = [[United States]]<br>[[Canada]]\n| slogan    =\n| airdate   =\n| frequency = [[Sirius XM Radio]] 309<br>[[Dish Network]] 6029\n| format    = [[Jam band|Jam Bands]]\n| owner     = [[Sirius XM Radio]]\n| class     = [[Satellite radio]] station\n| website   = [http://www.siriusxm.com/jamon SiriusXM: Jam On]\n}}\n'''''Jam On''''' is a [[jam band]] radio station on [[Sirius XM Radio]] channel 29 and [[Dish Network]] channel 6081. It has featured basketball player [[Bill Walton]] hosting a [[Grateful Dead]] show, [[hippie]] [[cultural icon|icon]] [[Wavy Gravy]], and pedal steel player [[Buddy Cage]] as a DJ.  It was formed in 2003 by Sirius VP Joel Salkowitz and programmer Lenny Bloch.  The original DJ's were Jonathan Schwartz, Stef Scamardo, and Adam Foley.\n\nBy fall 2010, Sirius XM moved ''Jam On'' to channel 81 on the Sirius side to make room for [[Pearl Jam Radio]] on channel 17.  However, Sirius tuners still list channel 81 under the old Cinemagic name, although from 2009\u20132010, that was ''[[The Strobe]]'' on Sirius 81.\n\nThe logo is designed to resemble that of jam band Phish.\n\nThe internet version can be biased toward \"traditional\" songs similar to the roots rock  style of the Grateful Dead, or to \"modern\" songs which are more electronically-based and experimental.\n\nIn June 2019, SiriusXM announced it would be moving JamOn to streaming only to make way for Phish Radio and that listeners could continue to listen to their favorite jam bands for an addition charge for their streaming service online or in the app only.\n\n==Core artists==\n* [[Phish]]\n* [[Gov't Mule]]\n* [[My Morning Jacket]]\n* [[Umphrey's McGee]]\n* [[moe.]]\n* [[Widespread Panic]]\n* [[The Allman Brothers Band]]\n* [[The Grateful Dead]]\n* [[The Disco Biscuits]]\n* [[The String Cheese Incident]]\n* [[Chris Robinson Brotherhood]]\n* [[Dave Matthews Band]]\n\n== Dave Matthews Band Radio ==\nBetween 2009-06-01 and 2009-06-08, the channel featured the music of rock band [[Dave Matthews Band]] 24/7 as well as exclusive interviews.  This  temporarily pre-empted normal programming on the channel.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Dave Matthews Band Radio To Air on SIRIUS XM Radio |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] via xmradio.com |accessdate=4 June 2009 |date=26 May 2009 |url=http://xmradio.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=press_releases&item=1729 |quote=\"Dave Matthews Band Radio\" to broadcast non-stop Dave Matthews Band music, plus exclusive stories from all four band members |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090831042619/http://xmradio.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=press_releases |archive-date=31 August 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Sirius Satellite Radio stations]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sirius.com/jamon Sirius Jam On]\n{{SiriusXM Channels (music)}}\n\n[[Category:Sirius Satellite Radio channels]]\n[[Category:XM Satellite Radio channels]]\n[[Category:Digital-only radio stations]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 2003]]\n\n\n{{US-radio-station-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jam_On"}
